      <section id="tdee">
        <h2>What is TDEE? (the number that actually matters)</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>TDEE — Total Daily Energy Expenditure</strong> — is the total number of
          calories your body burns in an entire day. Not just during exercise, but everything:
          breathing, digesting, walking to the kitchen, fidgeting in your chair, sleeping.
        </p>
        <p>
          TDEE is made up of four components:
        </p>

        <h3>1. BMR — Basal Metabolic Rate (60-70% of TDEE)</h3>
        <p>
          The calories your body burns just being alive: heart pumping, lungs breathing,
          cells repairing, brain functioning. Even if you lay in bed all day, your body
          burns this much. For most adults, BMR is 1,200-2,000 calories. Taller, heavier,
          younger, and more muscular people have higher BMR.
        </p>

        <h3>2. TEF — Thermic Effect of Food (8-15% of TDEE)</h3>
        <p>
          Digesting food costs energy. Protein takes the most energy to digest (20-30% of
          its calories). Carbs take 5-10%. Fats take 0-3%. This is one reason high-protein
          diets help with weight management — you burn more calories just processing the food.
        </p>

        <h3>3. EAT — Exercise Activity Thermogenesis (5-15% of TDEE)</h3>
        <p>
          The calories burned during intentional exercise: gym, running, yoga, sports.
          Despite what fitness marketing suggests, this is usually the <em>smallest</em>
          variable component of TDEE. A 30-minute run burns about 300 calories — which
          is one samosa. Exercise matters for health, but diet drives weight loss.
        </p>

        <h3>4. NEAT — Non-Exercise Activity Thermogenesis (15-30% of TDEE)</h3>
        <p>
          The unsung hero. NEAT is everything you do that isn't sleeping, eating, or
          exercising: walking to the bus, typing, cooking, standing, even fidgeting. NEAT
          can vary by 500-1,000 calories/day between a desk worker and someone with an active
          job. This is why "take 10,000 steps daily" advice is so effective — it boosts NEAT.
        </p>

        <div class="callout">
          <strong>📊 The math:</strong>
          TDEE = BMR + TEF + EAT + NEAT<br><br>
          For a typical Indian office worker (30 years, 70 kg, 170 cm):<br>
          BMR (~1,650) + TEF (~200) + EAT (~200) + NEAT (~350) = <strong>TDEE ≈ 2,400 calories/day</strong><br><br>
          Calculate yours: <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie / TDEE Calculator →</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="bmr">
        <h2>How your body burns calories: BMR formulas</h2>
        <p>
          Two main formulas are used to estimate BMR. Both are reasonably accurate for most
          people:
        </p>

        <h3>Mifflin-St Jeor equation (most widely recommended)</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Men:</strong> BMR = (10 × weight in kg) + (6.25 × height in cm) - (5 × age) + 5
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Women:</strong> BMR = (10 × weight in kg) + (6.25 × height in cm) - (5 × age) - 161
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Example:</strong> 30-year-old man, 75 kg, 175 cm:<br>
          BMR = (10 × 75) + (6.25 × 175) - (5 × 30) + 5 = 750 + 1,093.75 - 150 + 5 = <strong>1,699 calories</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Harris-Benedict equation (older, slightly less accurate)</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Men:</strong> BMR = 88.362 + (13.397 × weight) + (4.799 × height) - (5.677 × age)
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Women:</strong> BMR = 447.593 + (9.247 × weight) + (3.098 × height) - (4.330 × age)
        </p>

        <h3>From BMR to TDEE: the activity multiplier</h3>
        <p>
          Once you know BMR, multiply by your activity level:
        </p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Activity level</th>
                <th>Multiplier</th>
                <th>Description</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Sedentary</td>
                <td>1.2</td>
                <td>Desk job, no exercise, minimal walking</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Lightly active</td>
                <td>1.375</td>
                <td>Light exercise 1-3 days/week or walking 4,000-7,000 steps</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Moderately active</td>
                <td>1.55</td>
                <td>Moderate exercise 3-5 days/week, 7,000-10,000 steps</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Very active</td>
                <td>1.725</td>
                <td>Hard exercise 6-7 days/week or physical job</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Extremely active</td>
                <td>1.9</td>
                <td>Athlete-level training or very physical job + exercise</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>Be honest about your activity level.</strong> Most people overestimate.
          If you work a desk job and exercise 3 times a week for 30 minutes, you're
          "lightly active" not "moderately active." Overestimating activity is the #1 reason
          calorie calculations fail.
        </p>

        <p>
          Our <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie Calculator</a> uses Mifflin-St Jeor
          and applies the correct multiplier automatically. Enter your details once, get
          all the numbers.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="calculate">
        <h2>How to calculate your exact daily calories</h2>
        <p>
          Here's the step-by-step process:
        </p>

        <h3>Step 1: Calculate your BMR</h3>
        <p>
          Use the Mifflin-St Jeor formula above, or just use our
          <a href="/calculator/calorie/">calculator</a> which does it automatically.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 2: Multiply by activity factor</h3>
        <p>
          BMR × activity multiplier = your TDEE (maintenance calories).
        </p>

        <h3>Step 3: Adjust for your goal</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Maintain weight:</strong> Eat at your TDEE</li>
          <li><strong>Lose weight:</strong> Eat 300-500 calories below TDEE (calorie deficit)</li>
          <li><strong>Gain weight:</strong> Eat 300-500 calories above TDEE (calorie surplus)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 4: Set your macros</h3>
        <p>
          Calories tell you how much to eat. Macros tell you what to eat. Use our
          <a href="/calculator/macro/">Macro Calculator</a> to split your calories into
          protein, carbs, and fat based on your goal.
        </p>

        <h3>Step 5: Track and adjust</h3>
        <p>
          The formula gives you a starting point. Track your weight for 2 weeks. If you're
          not losing/gaining as expected, adjust by 100-200 calories. Bodies aren't perfect
          calculators — real-world results matter more than formulas.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="goals">
        <h2>Calories for weight loss, maintenance, and gain</h2>

        <h3>For weight loss: the calorie deficit</h3>
        <p>
          To lose fat, you must eat fewer calories than your body burns. This forces your
          body to use stored energy (fat). The size of the deficit determines the speed of
          weight loss:
        </p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Daily deficit</th>
                <th>Weekly fat loss</th>
                <th>Monthly fat loss</th>
                <th>Sustainable?</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>250 calories</td>
                <td>~0.25 kg</td>
                <td>~1 kg</td>
                <td>Very sustainable</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>500 calories</td>
                <td>~0.45 kg</td>
                <td>~2 kg</td>
                <td>Sustainable for most</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>750 calories</td>
                <td>~0.7 kg</td>
                <td>~3 kg</td>
                <td>Aggressive, hard to maintain</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>1,000+ calories</td>
                <td>~1 kg</td>
                <td>~4 kg</td>
                <td>Not recommended — muscle loss risk</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong>The sweet spot:</strong> 300-500 calorie deficit. Aggressive enough to see
          results in 2-3 weeks, sustainable enough to maintain for months. Going below 1,200
          calories (women) or 1,500 calories (men) is not recommended without medical
          supervision.
        </p>
        <p>
          Check your <a href="/calculator/bmi/">BMI</a> and
          <a href="/calculator/ideal-weight/">ideal weight</a> to set a realistic target
          before starting a deficit.
        </p>

        <h3>For maintenance: the equilibrium</h3>
        <p>
          Eating at TDEE means weight stays roughly stable. This is your "cruise" mode —
          ideal after reaching a goal weight. Weight may fluctuate 1-2 kg daily due to water,
          food volume, and sodium. Don't panic at daily changes; track weekly averages.
        </p>

        <h3>For weight gain: the calorie surplus</h3>
        <p>
          To build muscle, eat 300-500 calories above TDEE combined with resistance training.
          Without strength training, excess calories become fat. With proper training and
          adequate protein (1.6-2.2g per kg bodyweight), most of the gain will be muscle.
        </p>
        <p>
          Use our <a href="/calculator/macro/">Macro Calculator</a> to ensure you're getting
          enough protein for muscle building.
        </p>
      </section>

