      <section id="macros">
        <h2>Macros: why calories alone aren't enough</h2>
        <p>
          Calories determine <em>how much</em> to eat. <strong>Macronutrients</strong>
          (protein, carbohydrates, fat) determine <em>what</em> to eat. Two diets at 2,000
          calories can produce very different body composition results.
        </p>

        <h3>Protein: the most important macro</h3>
        <p>
          Protein preserves muscle during weight loss, builds muscle during weight gain,
          and keeps you feeling full longer. Indian diets are chronically low in protein —
          the average Indian consumes 0.6-0.8g per kg bodyweight, while optimal intake is
          1.2-2.0g per kg.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Target:</strong> 1.2g per kg bodyweight (maintenance), 1.6-2.0g per kg
          (muscle building or weight loss). For a 70 kg person, that's 84-140g protein daily.
        </p>
        <p>
          Good Indian protein sources: paneer (18g per 100g), eggs (6g each), chicken
          (27g per 100g), dal (8-9g per cup), soy chunks (52g per 100g), curd (4g per 100g),
          whey protein (24g per scoop).
        </p>

        <h3>Carbohydrates: your energy source</h3>
        <p>
          Indian diets are naturally carb-heavy (rice, roti, potatoes). Carbs aren't bad —
          they fuel activity and brain function. But excess carbs beyond your energy needs
          get stored as fat.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Target:</strong> 40-55% of total calories. At 2,000 calories, that's
          200-275g carbs (from rice, roti, vegetables, fruits — not sugar and maida).
        </p>

        <h3>Fats: essential but calorie-dense</h3>
        <p>
          Fats are necessary for hormones, vitamin absorption, and brain health. But fat
          has 9 calories per gram (vs 4 for protein and carbs) — so small amounts add up
          fast. One tablespoon of ghee or oil is 120 calories.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Target:</strong> 20-35% of total calories. At 2,000 calories, that's
          44-78g fat. Include healthy fats: ghee (moderate), nuts, seeds, mustard oil,
          coconut oil, fatty fish.
        </p>

        <p>
          Use our <a href="/calculator/macro/">Macro Calculator</a> to get your exact
          protein, carb, and fat targets based on your calorie goal and preferences.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="meal-plan">
        <h2>Sample Indian meal plans</h2>
        <p>
          These are framework templates — adjust portions and foods to your preferences.
          The goal is to show that Indian food can fit any calorie target with smart choices.
        </p>

        <h3>1,500 calorie plan (weight loss for most women)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Breakfast (350 cal):</strong> 2 idli + sambar + 1 cup chai (no sugar)</li>
          <li><strong>Mid-morning (100 cal):</strong> 1 small fruit (banana or apple)</li>
          <li><strong>Lunch (450 cal):</strong> 2 roti + 1 cup dal + sabzi + small salad</li>
          <li><strong>Evening snack (100 cal):</strong> Handful of roasted chana or makhana</li>
          <li><strong>Dinner (400 cal):</strong> 1 cup rice + 1 cup chicken/egg curry + raita</li>
          <li><strong>Before bed (100 cal):</strong> 1 glass warm milk (or skip)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2,000 calorie plan (maintenance for most adults)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Breakfast (450 cal):</strong> 2 egg omelette + 2 toast + chai with milk</li>
          <li><strong>Mid-morning (150 cal):</strong> Fruit + handful of almonds (10-12)</li>
          <li><strong>Lunch (550 cal):</strong> 1.5 cups rice + rajma + sabzi + curd</li>
          <li><strong>Evening snack (150 cal):</strong> Sprouts chaat or dhokla (3 pieces)</li>
          <li><strong>Dinner (550 cal):</strong> 2 roti + paneer sabzi + dal + salad</li>
          <li><strong>Before bed (150 cal):</strong> Glass of milk + 1 tsp honey (or skip)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2,500 calorie plan (active men or weight gain)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Breakfast (500 cal):</strong> Poha with peanuts + 2 boiled eggs + banana + chai</li>
          <li><strong>Mid-morning (200 cal):</strong> Protein shake or curd + fruit bowl</li>
          <li><strong>Lunch (700 cal):</strong> 2 cups rice + chicken curry + dal + sabzi + raita</li>
          <li><strong>Evening snack (200 cal):</strong> Peanut butter toast or chana + makhana</li>
          <li><strong>Dinner (650 cal):</strong> 3 roti + egg bhurji + palak paneer + salad</li>
          <li><strong>Before bed (250 cal):</strong> Banana shake with milk + 10 almonds</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Track your intake for one week using a food diary or app. Then adjust based on
          actual weight changes. Our <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie Calculator</a>
          gives you the target; consistency and tracking close the gap.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="mistakes">
        <h2>7 calorie counting mistakes to avoid</h2>

        <h3>1. Not counting cooking oil</h3>
        <p>
          Indian cooking uses generous oil and ghee. One tablespoon = 120 calories. A typical
          home-cooked meal uses 2-3 tablespoons — that's 240-360 <em>invisible</em> calories
          you're probably not counting. Restaurant food uses even more.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Ignoring chai and beverages</h3>
        <p>
          Three cups of chai daily = 210-300 calories. Add a sweet lassi or cold coffee and
          you're at 500+ calories from drinks alone. Liquid calories don't trigger fullness
          signals, so they don't reduce your food intake.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Overestimating exercise calories</h3>
        <p>
          Gym machines and fitness apps overestimate calories burned by 20-50%. A 30-minute
          walk doesn't earn you a samosa. Don't "eat back" exercise calories — your TDEE
          activity multiplier already accounts for regular exercise.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Weekend amnesia</h3>
        <p>
          Eating 1,800 calories Monday-Friday and 3,500 on Saturday-Sunday averages out to
          2,286/day — potentially above your deficit target. One restaurant buffet or wedding
          meal can undo a week of careful eating if it becomes a regular pattern.
        </p>

        <h3>5. Choosing "low fat" over "right calories"</h3>
        <p>
          Low-fat products often compensate with added sugar. A "low-fat" mango yogurt can
          have more calories than full-fat plain curd. Read nutrition labels, not marketing
          claims. Total calories and protein content matter more than fat percentage.
        </p>

        <h3>6. Using generic "Indian thali" calorie counts</h3>
        <p>
          Online calorie databases often list "Indian thali: 800 calories." But thalis
          vary enormously: a simple dal-roti-sabzi home meal is 400-500 calories. A
          restaurant Rajasthani thali with 12 items and ghee is 1,500+. Always estimate
          your specific foods, not generic meal labels.
        </p>

        <h3>7. Aiming for perfection instead of consistency</h3>
        <p>
          You don't need to hit 2,000 calories exactly every day. Hitting 1,900-2,100 range
          consistently is far more effective than alternating between 1,500 and 2,800.
          Consistency over weeks matters more than precision on any single day.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="faq">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many calories should I eat a day to lose weight?</h3>
          <p>
            Eat 300-500 calories below your TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure). For most
            adults this means 1,400-2,200 calories depending on size and activity. Calculate
            your specific number with our
            <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie Calculator</a>. Never go below 1,200
            (women) or 1,500 (men) without medical guidance.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is 1,200 calories enough for an Indian woman?</h3>
          <p>
            1,200 calories is the absolute minimum recommended for women, suitable only for
            very petite, sedentary women under medical supervision. Most Indian women need
            1,500-2,000 calories even for weight loss. Going too low causes muscle loss,
            metabolic slowdown, nutrient deficiency, and is not sustainable. Aim for a
            moderate deficit instead.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many calories in 1 roti?</h3>
          <p>
            One medium wheat roti (made from about 30g atta) contains approximately 70-80
            calories. A thicker or larger roti can be 90-110 calories. Adding ghee or
            butter adds 40-50 calories per teaspoon. Most adults eat 2-4 rotis per meal,
            totaling 140-400+ calories from roti alone.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many calories in 1 cup rice?</h3>
          <p>
            One cup of cooked white rice (approximately 200g) has 200-240 calories. Brown
            rice is similar in calories (215-250) but has more fiber and micronutrients.
            Most Indians eat 1-2 cups per meal, so rice contributes 200-480 calories per
            sitting.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How do I count calories in homemade Indian food?</h3>
          <p>
            Break each dish into ingredients: dal = lentils (calories by weight) + oil used
            + tempering (tadka) ingredients. Use our food chart above as reference. Key tip:
            measure the oil you cook with — this is where most hidden calories come from in
            Indian cooking. One tablespoon of any oil or ghee adds 120 calories.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Should I count calories or just eat healthy?</h3>
          <p>
            Both approaches work. Calorie counting is more precise but requires effort.
            "Eating healthy" (whole foods, lean protein, vegetables, minimal processed food)
            can work without counting — but portion control is still needed. If you've been
            eating healthy but not losing weight, counting for 2-4 weeks reveals where the
            excess calories are hiding.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Do I need to count calories forever?</h3>
          <p>
            No. Count for 4-8 weeks to learn portion sizes and calorie values of foods you
            regularly eat. After that, most people develop enough intuition to estimate
            meals without tracking. Revisit tracking if weight stalls or goals change.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many calories should I eat to gain muscle?</h3>
          <p>
            Eat 300-500 calories above your TDEE while consuming 1.6-2.0g protein per kg
            bodyweight and doing progressive resistance training. Without adequate protein
            and training, extra calories become fat, not muscle. Calculate your surplus
            with our <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie Calculator</a> and macros with
            our <a href="/calculator/macro/">Macro Calculator</a>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Why am I not losing weight even in a calorie deficit?</h3>
          <p>
            Common reasons: underestimating calories (not counting oil, snacks, weekends),
            overestimating activity level, water retention masking fat loss (weigh weekly not
            daily), metabolic adaptation after prolonged dieting (take a diet break for 1-2
            weeks at maintenance), or medical conditions (thyroid, PCOS — consult a doctor).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is my BMR and why does it matter?</h3>
          <p>
            BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate) is the calories your body burns at complete rest —
            just keeping you alive. It's 60-70% of your total daily burn. Knowing your BMR
            helps set a safe calorie floor: eating below BMR for extended periods is risky
            and counterproductive. Our <a href="/calculator/calorie/">Calorie Calculator</a>
            shows both BMR and TDEE.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

